===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A very small piece of matter, a [[fragment]]; especially, the smallest possible part of something. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
# {{lb|en|physics}} Any of various physical objects making up the constituent parts of an [[atom]]; an [[elementary particle]] or [[subatomic particle]]. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}
#* '''2011''', {{w|Brian Cox (physicist)|Brian Cox}} & Jeff Forshaw, ''The Quantum Universe'', Allen Lane 2011, p. 55:
#*: What, he asked himself, does quantum theory have to say about the familiar properties of '''particles''' such as position?
#* {{quote-magazine|year=2012|month=March-April
|author={{w|Jeremy Bernstein}}
|title=A Palette of Particles
|volume=100|issue=2|page=146
|magazine={{w|American Scientist}}
|url=http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2012/2/a-palette-of-particles
|passage=The physics of elementary '''particles''' in the 20th century was distinguished by the observation of '''particles''' whose existence had been predicted by theorists sometimes decades earlier.}}
# {{lb|en|linguistics}} A word that has a particular [[grammatical]] [[function]] but does not obviously belong to any particular [[part of speech]], such as the word ''to'' in English [[infinitive]]s or ''[[O]]'' as a [[vocative]] particle.
#* {{quote-web
|date=1965-06-04
|author=Shigeyuki Kuroda
